        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer2696910466" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer18249771020714472961">A solid 3.5 if this were possible.<br/>I remember seeing the movie shortly after it came out, and loving it. Does it in any way resemble the book? I can’t make that comparison anymore because too much time has elapsed in between.<br/>The story at the heart of the book is heart-warming, pulling the reader in and keeping you hooked to its main protagonists, the 14-year old boy, his mother and his school teacher. The book’s subject is mainly about the boy’s school project which ends up having wide-ranging ef</span>
  <span id="freeText18249771020714472961" style="display:none">A solid 3.5 if this were possible.<br />I remember seeing the movie shortly after it came out, and loving it. Does it in any way resemble the book? I can’t make that comparison anymore because too much time has elapsed in between.<br />The story at the heart of the book is heart-warming, pulling the reader in and keeping you hooked to its main protagonists, the 14-year old boy, his mother and his school teacher. The book’s subject is mainly about the boy’s school project which ends up having wide-ranging effects to which the reader is privy, but not the boy himself until much later...<br />[I love the concept of his project and in many little ways and actions in life apply it and often see it being applied].<br />What stopped me from giving the book a solid 4* rating was not so much the author’s writing style as the partitioning of the different stories, which to me came across choppy and disconcerting.<br />The author however at all times imbues the different characters in her book with unique personalities, esp the 14 year old Trevor who comes across immensely lovable, caring and humorous.</span>
  <a data-text-id="18249771020714472961" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


